request.description:
A `GET` request to the `/simulations` endpoint will return an object with pagination properties and a `results` array of simulations owned by the User.

The pagination properties are:

*   `count`: total number of simulations received;
*   `next`: url of the next page of the simulation list;
*   `previous`: url of the previous page of the simulation list.


The urls will be `null` when the number of simulations is less than the minimum required for a page.

The list view is more simplified than the detailed view, as such it'll only show these properties:

*   `id`;
*   `owner`;
*   `title`;
*   `date_created`
*   `url`.


If the User is also an Admin, then all simulations are returned.

item.description:
The `/simulations` endpoint handles everything related to simulations: create, read, and execute.

A Simulation contains the following properties:

*   `id`: the id of the simulation;
*   `owner`: the username of the User that owns the simulation;
*   `title`: a user defined title for the simulation;
*   `description`: a user defined description for the simulation;
*   `date_created`: the date that the simulation was created (GMT+0);
*   `url`: the url of the simulation;
*   `execute`: the url to execute the simulation;
*   `modeller_input`: the url of the simulation's modeller input;
*   `modeller_output`: the url of the simulation's modeller output;
*   `simulator_output`: the url of the simulation's simulator output;
*   `postprocessor_input`: the url of the simulation's postprocessor input;
*   `postprocessor_output`: the url of the simulation's postprocessor output.

request.description:
The `/modeller-input/{id}` endpoint contains the data for the simulation's modeller input. When creating a new simulation, the `scenario_analysis_input` property is saved here.

The response contains the following properties:
- `simulation`: the id of the related simulation;
- `url`: the url of the modeller input;
- `scenario_analysis_input`: the input for the Scenario Analysis simulation.

